{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472919","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472919"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:02:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:02:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1587"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1587"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.29,0.08,0.08,0.05,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28859"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1587"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1587"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15056"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"672"},{"type":"tags","id":"1397"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7170"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7240"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28859","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/28859"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 13-year-old boy presents with painful toes and difficulties in weight-bearing on the medial aspect of the foot. These changes to the toes have been present for several weeks.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trimming of affected nail and antiseptic dressing","Soaking of feet in soapy water and high potency topical corticosteroids","Topical antibiotics on affected area","25% silver nitrate on granulation tissue","Partial nail bed excision with phenol matricetomy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis boy has presented with bilateral ingrown toenails. Generally, first line therapy for patients with mild to moderate ingrown toenails would be conservative treatment measures such as \u003Cstrong\u003Etrimming of the affected distal nail followed by antiseptic dressing or soaking of the feet in warm, soapy water and high potency topical corticosteroids.\u003C/strong\u003E Other, less common conservative options include the application of \u003Cstrong\u003E25% silver nitrate solution \u003C/strong\u003Eapplied to the granulation tissue, however this is rarely used in clinical practice nowadays.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHowever, in this instance, the toes are visibly erythematous, with associated granulation tissue and swelling of the lateral aspects of the toes. This would be a more severe presentation and requires surgical intervention. Some form of lateral \u003Cstrong\u003Enail bed excision\u003C/strong\u003E and removal of the granulation tissue is required. There are many different surgical techniques that can be utilised depending on surgeon preference. The use of \u003Cstrong\u003Etopical 88% phenol \u003C/strong\u003Eduring the procedure is to induce destruction of nail matrix cells to prevent further nail growth in the treated area.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are only indicated if there is evidence of spreading cellulitis or lymphangitis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["For mild to moderate ingrown toenails, a conservative treatment is recommended.","Severe ingrown toenails includes the formation of granulation tissue, and generally requires surgical intervention."],"references":["Bryant A, Knox A. Ingrown toenails: the role of the GP. Australian Family Physician. 2015 Mar;44(3):102-5."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15056"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1587"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17519"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17519","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17519"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fd2c7ce6-17b0-4d81-920b-dcf21407df87.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/fd2c7ce6-17b0-4d81-920b-dcf21407df87.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":640,"height":480}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"15056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/15056"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-10-03T22:44:54+10:30","updatedAt":"2022-10-03T22:44:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1587"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"28859"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description"